[normal]AF0107[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence submitted by[bold] 
[normal]David Wolfe QC[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Executive Summary:[bold] 
[normal]I am a barrister with extensive practical expertise of
[normal] academies and the law. 
[normal]My submission identifies some of the legal/governance 
[normal]issues arising from the process of establishing and operating different types of academies/free schools (including issues as to transparency, public participation and tendering).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My background and this submission:[bold]Since 1992, I have practised as a barrist
[normal]er specialising in, among other things, education law. I have also been a member of a Local Education Authority, a governor at five schools and a Further Education College, and a part time judge of the Special Educational Needs and Disability Tribunal.
[normal]In 
[normal]the course of my practice as a lawyer I have advised and acted for (including in legal proceedings) a great many parents, parents’ groups, governing bodies, head teachers, unions, NGOs and local authorities on issues relating to school organisation/re-orga
[normal]nisation 
[normal]and governance 
[normal]including, in particular (since 2005) in relation to academies and free schools. 
[normal]I am the author of the blog on academies/free schools and the law: 
[normal]www.acanofworms.org.uk
[normal] which has been
[normal] looked at by an average of over 1,000 people per week since I set it up in October 2011.
[normal]What follows is my summary response on each of the points I understand to be under consideration by the Select Committee. I have only commented on those things on whi
[normal]ch I have direct relevant expertise based on my personal experience
[normal] and focussed my points on legal/governance aspects
[normal]. 
[normal]I would be very happy to elaborate as requested. 
[normal]I would be pleased to assist by giving oral evidence to the Committee.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“The [bold]effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes;”[bold]“The process for approving, compell[bold]ing and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors;”[bold]              [bold]Academy conversion[bold]Sponsors[bold]Free schools[bold]“The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands;”[bold]“The functions [bold]and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in sup[bold]port for schools at this level;”[bold]“What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements;”[bold]“The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply; a[bold]nd what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole;”[bold]“What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools.”[bold]&#xa0;[bold]December 2013
